        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1959-06-08T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1959-06-08T05:00:00-05:00" n="371"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d371">
                <head>371. Telegram From Secretary of State <persName corresp="#p_HCA1" type="from"
                        >Herter</persName> to the <gloss type="to">Embassy in Germany</gloss>
                    <note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d371fn0">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 762.00/6–859. Secret; Priority. Repeated to Berlin, London, Moscow,
                        Paris, and the Department as <gloss target="#t_Cahto1">Cahto</gloss> 86,
                        which is the source text.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Geneva</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1959-06-08T11:00:00+01:00">June 8, 1959, 11 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>178. Eyes only Chiefs of Mission. Paris pass <gloss target="#t_USRO1"
                        >USRO</gloss> eyes only for Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_BWR1"
                        >Burgess</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_TRL1">Thurston</persName> for
                        <persName corresp="#p_NGL1">Norstad</persName>. Reference Bonn’s 125 to
                        Geneva.<note n="1" xml:id="d371fn1">Telegram 125, June 6, agreed with the
                        reservations that <persName corresp="#p_HMGB1">Hamlett</persName>, <persName
                            corresp="#p_NGL1">Norstad</persName>, and <persName corresp="#p_BW2"
                            >Brandt</persName> had expressed about limiting the size of the garrison
                        in Berlin, but stated that if the West did agree to a limitation, this
                        function would not be shared or exercised by the Soviet Union. (<hi
                            rend="italic">Ibid.</hi>, 762.00/6–659)</note>
                </p>
                <p>I have very much in mind <persName corresp="#p_HMGB1">Hamlett</persName>’s views
                    re limitation Berlin garrisons as well as <persName corresp="#p_NGL1"
                        >Norstad</persName>’s expressed concerns. In first place we have never
                    considered specific agreement with Soviets on numbers since this would limit our
                    freedom possible future action and open door to Soviet entrance West Berlin on
                    claim rights of inspection. Hence any statement contemplated would take form
                    unilateral declarative statement of intentions. Similarly all Western
                    delegations are thinking in terms intention not exceed existing figures and not
                    in terms any reduction in force unless in Western judgment future developments
                    in Berlin should justify.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_HCA1">Herter</persName>
                </p>
            </div>
